Here he perfectly exemplifies that connexion between connoisseurship and play which Fielding discovers in Book xiii. of Tom Jones.¹ An anecdote of C. J. Fox aptly exhibits the final couplet in action, and proves that fifty years later, at least, the same convenient code was in operation. Fox once Won about eight thousand pounds at cards. Thereupon an eager creditor promptly presented himself, and pressed for payment. “ Impossible‚ Sir,’' replied Fox, “I must first discharge my debts of honour.’' The creditor expostulated. “Well, Sir, give me your bond.’' The bond was delivered to Fox, who tore it up and flung the pieces into the fire. “ Now, Sir,'' said he, “my debt to you is a debt of honour,'’ and immediately paid him.2
